### Advanced Research Methods lecture
*March 2025 at RSM*

This presentation was part of the Advanced Research Methods course. The is the first of two presentations that the Accounting and Finance department sahre with the students. The goal is to provide an overview of research in the field of accounting and finance, and to introduce the students to some of research methods that they could use in their own BSc projects. The goal is to provide a gentle introduction to the research process and to inspire students to think about their own research projects.

[Advanced Research Methods](/presentations/Advance research methods.html)
:::



<!-- ::: {.presentation-card}
### Education Day 2025

*February 2025 at RSM*

This presentation showcases how I envision to implement LLMs in the feedback process during MSc thesis supervision. Importantly, this is one of my side-hustles, so I'll update it as time permits. My ambition is to bring it to production and make it available to all thesis supervisors - in the accounting department at least. I want to stress that this is far away from being a reality, but I am (was) excited to share my vision during our departmental Education Day. 

I plan to include more details about the practical steps and potential challenges in the implementation. Additionally, I aim to outline potential use cases, e.g. different prompts for different stages of the thesis trajectory, and gather feedback from peers to refine this idea further.

[Education Day 2025](/presentations/edu_day_2025_slides.html)
::: -->

::: {.presentation-card}
### Data & Coding
*September 2024 at RSM*

The presentation below was meant to bring our incoming academic director up to speed with the current developments in our new Data and Coding online course. By now, it ran for the first time and I hopefully have the time to update the slides to reflect the experiences and feedback from the first run. 

[Data and coding course](/presentations/catch_up.html)
:::

